 fairly inexperienced and all - no formal training of any sort. so i was wondering if maybe somebody could answer this question. sorry if i sound like an idiot.<br>
<br>
what is the deal with all the different pencil weights? <br>
<br>
anything in the &quot;hard&quot; category is nigh impossible to erase, tears up the paper, and generally leaves very little graphite for the effort. anything in the &quot;soft&quot; end of the spectrum is like spreading mud on the paper, also very difficult to erase, and smears over everything if your hand ever touches the paper again. <br>
<br>
and of course, good old yellow #2HB acts like a real pencil. oh wait, it is. <br>
<br>
so. i ask you. what do you actually use the other ones for? specifically in regards to pencil drawings made for CG work where shading will be accomplished through color. (i personal dislike all forms of monochrome art - everything needs a little color) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uspikescafe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SpikesCafe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.spikescafe.com/shell.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Gamera</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/11/01 3:22:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2322.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.spikescafe.com/spikes/b_spike2.gif height=95 width=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: pencil weights</span><hr size=1> So far as I understand...<br>
